# Murder of Emmett Till Interviews

## Thumbnail

![Murder of Emmett Till](https://s3.amazonaws.com/americanarchive.org/special-collections/AX0007_Emmett_Till.jpg "Murder of Emmett Till")

## Summary

The <em>Murder of Emmett Till</em> Interviews Collection is made up of 40 raw interviews from the award-winning 2003 <em>American Experience</em> documentary of the same name. The film, which chronicled the story of Emmett Till, a 14-year-old who was murdered on August 28, 1955 after being accused of whistling at a white woman, also discussed how Till became an icon of persecution and injustice during the Civil Rights Movement. The <em> Murder of Emmett Till</em> interviews paint a fuller picture of the Jim Crow South, the Mississippi community in which the murder took place, and contains intimate recollections of those who knew Emmett Till. Guests include family and friends of Emmett Till, as well as journalists and politicians, including Mamie Till Mobley, Emmett Till's mother and activist for Civil Rights; Wheeler Parker, Emmett Till's cousin; Ernest Withers, a photographer known for his photos of the segregated South; Willie Reed, who risked his life by testifying against Emmett Till's murderers; and Clarence Strider, Jr., son of the Tallahatchie County Sheriff at the time of the murder. Topics include segregation, Jim Crow, lynching and violence, the American judicial system, journalism, the American South, and the Civil Rights Movement.  

## Background

The <em>Murder of Emmett Till</em> interviews were conducted in 2003 for the <em>American Experience</em> documentary of the same name. Winner of a Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for Nonfiction Programming, the Sundance Film Festival Special Jury Prize, and the George Foster Peabody Award for his work on <em>The Murder of Emmett Till</em>, Stanley Nelson, Jr. served as the documentary's Director. <em>American Experience</em>, PBS' flagship history documentary series, premiered in 1988 and is produced at WGBH in Boston. In 2017, the WGBH Media Library and Archives digitized the <em>Murder of Emmett Till</em> interviews and in 2018 submitted them to the American Archive of Public Broadcasting.

